Architecture plan for issues #73-#76

Project baseline
- Product name is alex-1883-test-33.
- Monorepo uses Node ESM workspaces: frontend/ is React + Vite, backend/ is Express.
- Backend serves frontend/dist for the SPA and should expose production APIs under /api/*.
- Existing backend modules cover Google OAuth, JWT auth, users/profile data, image uploads, posts, feed, follows, likes, and comments, but the main Express app currently mounts only health/static handling.
- Existing frontend modules cover auth context/client, sign-in flow, profile page, feed page, post card, image composer, follow toggle, like toggle, and comment thread.

Issue order and dependencies
1. #73 mounts all existing backend feature routers into backend/src/app.mjs under a unified /api prefix and wires JWT authentication middleware where routes require a user.
2. #74 uses the backend auth entry points from #73 to complete the top-right Sign in / signed-in user menu behavior.
3. #75 replaces route-directory/placeholder views with real Feed, Profile, and Post detail pages that call the mounted backend APIs.
4. #76 runs the deployed end-to-end path: login -> image post -> feed -> like/comment/follow, fixing any integration gaps left by #73-#75.

Backend structure
- Keep backend/src/app.mjs as the production Express composition root.
- Mount feature route handlers under /api using thin adapters rather than duplicating service logic.
- Preserve /healthz and /api/healthz.
- Use existing ApiError/toErrorResponse contracts and log unexpected 500s before responding.
- Keep PostgreSQL as the only persistent store through Prisma and DATABASE_URL.
- Keep S3-compatible Object Storage as the only binary image storage path through the existing storage client.

Frontend structure
- Keep React route ownership in frontend/src/App.mjs and shared navigation in frontend/src/layout/.
- Centralize API URL changes in frontend/src/auth/api-client.mjs so pages do not hardcode divergent paths.
- Reuse existing feature components for Feed, Profile, Post detail, upload composer, likes, comments, and follows.
- The topbar should use Auth Context state; unauthenticated users see Sign in, authenticated users see their account menu.

Key design decisions
- API paths should be unambiguous /api/* routes so SPA fallback never intercepts JSON endpoints.
- Protected frontend routes should fail into a coherent sign-in flow instead of a not-found page.
- Do not fabricate external OAuth or Object Storage credentials; unavailable external integrations should surface clearly.
- Favor narrow adapters and composition over rewrites because the feature modules already exist.
